AB  - For a Bayesian approach to be useful, the priors and posteriors must be carefully interpreted to guarantee that the economic conclusions reached are justified; otherwise, the approach simply yields a set of summary statistics with little economic insight. The Bayesian approach to testing between different models of trend proposed in DeJong and Whiteman (1991) suffers from this shortcoming.
